	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>qwertymodo</b> [ Tue Aug 05, 2014 3:38 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: FreePCB board designing-WTF is going on???</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I know Gerber files have <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ann_Turner_Cook" class="postlink">nothing</a> to do with Brandy O'Bannon mystery novels. But in this analogy, would a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerber_format" class="postlink">Gerber file</a> be analogous to a PDF?</div><br />Yes.  They're basically vector image files that are used by the manufacturing plants to actually create the PCB's from your design.  There's no concept of &quot;components&quot; or &quot;connections&quot; it's just a single file per layer (top/bottom copper/soldermask/silkscreen) containing the shapes and dimensions of that particular layer.  PDF is quite an apropos analogy in that trying to find a program to edit a gerber file exported out of a PCB editor is like trying to find an application to edit a PDF that you exported out of Microsoft Word, instead of just editing the original .doc(x) file.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


